<vulnerability_guide>
  <title>SPF/DKIM/DMARC BYPASS</title>

  <critical>SPF, DKIM, and DMARC form the email authentication triad. Bypassing these controls enables email spoofing from trusted domains, successful phishing campaigns, and business email compromise. Misconfigurations are common - over 80% of Fortune 500 domains have exploitable email authentication gaps.</critical>

  <scope>
    - SPF record analysis and bypass
    - DKIM key weaknesses
    - DMARC policy circumvention
    - Subdomain exploitation
    - Display name spoofing
    - Reply-To and lookalike domains
  </scope>

  <methodology>
    1. SPF ANALYSIS
       {% raw %}
       # Query SPF record
       dig target.com TXT | grep spf
       nslookup -type=txt target.com

       # SPF Syntax analysis:
       # v=spf1 - Version
       # ip4:1.2.3.4 - Allowed IP
       # include:_spf.google.com - Include other SPF
       # a, mx - Use A/MX records
       # ~all - Softfail
       # -all - Hardfail
       # ?all - Neutral

       # Weak policies:
       # +all - Allow everything (terrible)
       # ~all - Softfail (often not enforced)
       # ?all - Neutral (no policy)
       # Missing SPF - No protection
       {% endraw %}

    2. DKIM ANALYSIS
       {% raw %}
       # Find DKIM selectors
       # Common selectors: default, google, selector1, s1, dkim

       dig selector._domainkey.target.com TXT
       dig google._domainkey.target.com TXT
       dig default._domainkey.target.com TXT

       # DKIM key analysis:
       # k=rsa - Key type
       # p=<base64> - Public key

       # Weak keys:
       # - RSA < 1024 bits (factorable)
       # - Missing key (t=y for testing)
       # - Overly permissive selectors

       # Check key strength
       # Decode base64, analyze RSA modulus
       {% endraw %}

    3. DMARC ANALYSIS
       {% raw %}
       # Query DMARC record
       dig _dmarc.target.com TXT

       # DMARC policy analysis:
       # p=none - Monitor only (no enforcement)
       # p=quarantine - Mark as spam
       # p=reject - Reject spoofed emails

       # sp= - Subdomain policy (often different)
       # rua= - Aggregate reports
       # ruf= - Forensic reports
       # pct= - Percentage to apply policy

       # Weak configurations:
       # p=none - No enforcement
       # pct=0 - Policy never applied
       # sp=none - Subdomains unprotected
       # Missing DMARC - No policy
       {% endraw %}

    4. SUBDOMAIN EXPLOITATION
       {% raw %}
       # Check subdomain SPF/DMARC

       # If main domain has DMARC p=reject
       # But sp=none or missing:
       # Spoof from subdomain.target.com

       dig _dmarc.mail.target.com TXT  # Often no record
       dig mail.target.com TXT  # SPF may be missing

       # Many organizations protect main domain
       # But forget about subdomains

       # Check for:
       # - No SPF on subdomains
       # - sp=none in main DMARC
       # - sp not specified (defaults to p, but check)
       {% endraw %}

    5. SPF INCLUDE EXPLOITATION
       {% raw %}
       # SPF includes create chains

       # If target includes: include:thirdparty.com
       # And you control thirdparty.com DNS
       # You can send as target.com

       # Trace include chain
       v=spf1 include:_spf.google.com include:partner.com ~all

       # Check each included domain
       dig _spf.google.com TXT

       # Expired/takeover domains in includes
       # If included domain is available
       # Register it, add your IP to SPF
       {% endraw %}
  </methodology>

  <advanced_techniques>
    <display_name_spoofing>
      {% raw %}
      # Most email clients show display name prominently

      # Legitimate email:
      From: "CEO <ceo@company.com>" <attacker@evil.com>

      # User sees: CEO <ceo@company.com>
      # Actual sender: attacker@evil.com

      # Variations:
      From: "CEO ceo@company.com" <attacker@evil.com>
      From: "Payroll <payroll@company.com>" <attacker@evil.com>

      # This bypasses SPF/DKIM/DMARC
      # Those check the actual domain, not display name
      {% endraw %}
    </display_name_spoofing>

    <reply_to_manipulation>
      {% raw %}
      # Replies go to Reply-To, not From

      # Legitimate From, malicious Reply-To
      From: support@company.com
      Reply-To: support@company-helpdesk.com  # Attacker domain

      # User sees legitimate company
      # Replies go to attacker

      # Combine with:
      # - Look-alike domain registration
      # - Typosquatting
      {% endraw %}
    </reply_to_manipulation>

    <partial_failure_exploitation>
      {% raw %}
      # Exploit SPF softfail (~all)

      # Many receivers don't enforce softfail
      # Only hardfail (-all) is blocked

      # If SPF has ~all:
      # Spoof and hope receiver doesn't enforce

      # DMARC p=none exploitation
      # Even with SPF fail
      # Email still delivered

      # pct=10 exploitation
      # Only 10% of messages get policy
      # Send many, some get through
      {% endraw %}
    </partial_failure_exploitation>

    <mailfrom_confusion>
      {% raw %}
      # SPF checks MAIL FROM (envelope)
      # DKIM checks d= domain
      # DMARC aligns these with From header

      # Misalignment attack:
      # MAIL FROM: attacker@evil.com (SPF pass for evil.com)
      # From: ceo@target.com (displayed to user)

      # If DMARC isn't enforced:
      # SPF passes, email delivered
      # User sees spoofed From

      # Null MAIL FROM
      # Some systems use <> as MAIL FROM
      # SPF may not apply
      {% endraw %}
    </mailfrom_confusion>

    <weak_dkim_exploitation>
      {% raw %}
      # Short RSA keys can be factored

      # 512-bit RSA: Factorable in hours
      # 768-bit RSA: Factorable with resources
      # 1024-bit RSA: Theoretically weak

      # Extract public key
      dig selector._domainkey.target.com TXT

      # Analyze key length
      # If short, factor to get private key
      # Sign emails as target.com

      # Testing mode exploitation
      # t=y means testing
      # Receivers may ignore failures
      {% endraw %}
    </weak_dkim_exploitation>
  </advanced_techniques>

  <detection>
    - Monitor DMARC aggregate reports
    - Alert on authentication failures
    - Track sender reputation changes
    - Implement strict DMARC policy
    - Use strong DKIM keys (2048-bit+)
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Analyze target's email authentication
    - Identify SPF/DKIM/DMARC weaknesses
    - Successfully spoof email
    - Demonstrate subdomain exploitation
    - Document bypass techniques
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - DMARC p=none is monitor-only - emails still delivered
    - ~all (softfail) is rarely enforced by receivers
    - Subdomains often lack protection even when main domain is secure
    - Display name spoofing bypasses all technical controls
    - Look-alike domains (company-help.com) are simple but effective
    - Check DMARC reports for what gets through
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>Email authentication is only as strong as its weakest link. A missing subdomain policy, softfail instead of hardfail, or p=none instead of p=reject all create spoofing opportunities. Display name spoofing bypasses everything technical. For truly protected email, you need p=reject, sp=reject, strong DKIM, and hardfail SPF across all domains and subdomains.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
